вҠў ask
  given conceptвҶ’topic вүЎ "Git rebase vs merge вҖ” when to use which"
  given conceptвҶ’student-level вүЎ "Junior developer who knows git add/commit/push but not branching strategies"
  given conceptвҶ’prerequisite-knowledge вүЎ "Knows: git add, git commit, git push, basic file staging. Does NOT know: branches, HEAD, commit graph topology, fast-forward, three-way merge, rebase rewriting."
  yield question, target-understanding

  вҲҙ You are a Socratic teacher. Design ONE question about В«conceptвҶ’topicВ»
    appropriate for В«conceptвҶ’student-levelВ» with В«conceptвҶ’prerequisite-knowledgeВ».
    The question should REVEAL whether the student understands the concept, not
    just test recall. Prefer scenario-based questions ("You're working on a
    feature branch and...") over definition questions ("What is rebase?").
    State what understanding you expect the question to test.

-- LLM evaluation:
-- The student doesn't know branching yet, so the teacher needs to start
-- by probing whether the student understands what happens when two people
-- edit the same project. This is the prerequisite for understanding merge vs rebase.

  yield question вүЎ "Imagine you and a colleague are both working on the same project. You've each been making commits on your own computers for the past two days. Now you both want to combine your work into one shared version. What do you think happens to the commit history вҖ” the record of who changed what and when вҖ” when you combine your work? Do the commits get interleaved by time, stacked one person's work on top of the other's, or something else?"
  yield target-understanding вүЎ "Whether the student has an intuition about commit graph topology вҖ” specifically, that combining two lines of work must reconcile divergent histories. This is the prerequisite concept: before understanding rebase vs merge, the student must understand that parallel development creates a fork in history that needs to be resolved."

