вҠў simulate-student
  given askвҶ’question вүЎ "Imagine you and a colleague are both working on the same project. You've each been making commits on your own computers for the past two days. Now you both want to combine your work into one shared version. What do you think happens to the commit history вҖ” the record of who changed what and when вҖ” when you combine your work? Do the commits get interleaved by time, stacked one person's work on top of the other's, or something else?"
  given conceptвҶ’student-level вүЎ "Junior developer who knows git add/commit/push but not branching strategies"
  given conceptвҶ’prerequisite-knowledge вүЎ "Knows: git add, git commit, git push, basic file staging. Does NOT know: branches, HEAD, commit graph topology, fast-forward, three-way merge, rebase rewriting."
  yield answer, confidence

  вҲҙ You are simulating a student at level В«conceptвҶ’student-levelВ» with
    knowledge В«conceptвҶ’prerequisite-knowledgeВ». Answer В«askвҶ’questionВ»
    as this student would вҖ” with partial knowledge, common misconceptions,
    and honest confusion. Do NOT give the correct answer unless the student
    at this level would actually know it. Express confidence: "confident",
    "unsure", or "guessing".

-- LLM evaluation:
-- A junior dev who only knows add/commit/push thinks of git as a single
-- linear timeline. They've probably experienced "git push" failing because
-- the remote is ahead, but they think of it as an error, not as divergent history.

  yield answer вүЎ "I think the commits would just get interleaved by time? Like, if I made a commit Monday morning and my colleague made one Monday afternoon, they'd show up in that order. It's like a shared timeline. But actually, I've run into problems before where git wouldn't let me push because my colleague already pushed something. I had to do a 'git pull' first and then push again. So maybe it's not automatic? I'm not really sure what happens when you pull вҖ” I think it just downloads their stuff and then my commits go on top?"
  yield confidence вүЎ "unsure"

-- oracle checks:
--   вҠЁ answer reflects the stated student level, not expert knowledge вҶ’ вң“
--     (thinks of linear timeline, confused about pull, doesn't know about branches)
--   вҠЁ confidence вҲҲ {"confident", "unsure", "guessing"} вҶ’ вң“ ("unsure")

