вҠў remedial-0
  given misconception вүЎ "Believes commit history is a single shared timeline ordered by wall-clock time вҖ” does not understand that each developer has an independent local history that diverges."
  yield corrected-understanding

  вҲҙ The student thinks all commits live on one shared timeline. Disprove this
    with a concrete counter-example: show two developers making commits at the
    same times but on different machines, producing two separate commit logs
    that only meet when they explicitly combine their work. Explain that each
    git clone has its OWN history вҖ” there is no shared clock.

  вҠЁ corrected-understanding directly addresses the timeline misconception

вҠў remedial-1
  given misconception вүЎ "Thinks 'git pull' simply downloads and stacks commits linearly вҖ” unaware that pull performs a merge (or rebase) to reconcile two divergent histories."
  yield corrected-understanding

  вҲҙ The student thinks pull just downloads and appends. Show what actually
    happens: pull = fetch + merge (by default). When histories diverge,
    merge creates a NEW commit that has TWO parents вҖ” one from each history.
    This is NOT stacking. Draw the before/after commit graph.

  вҠЁ corrected-understanding directly addresses the pull misconception

