вҠў remedial-0
  given misconception вүЎ "Believes commit history is a single shared timeline ordered by wall-clock time вҖ” does not understand that each developer has an independent local history that diverges."
  yield corrected-understanding

  вҲҙ The student thinks all commits live on one shared timeline. Disprove this
    with a concrete counter-example: show two developers making commits at the
    same times but on different machines, producing two separate commit logs
    that only meet when they explicitly combine their work...

-- LLM evaluation:

  yield corrected-understanding вүЎ "Counter-example: Alice and Bob both clone repo X at 9:00 AM. Alice commits A1 at 10am, A2 at 11am. Bob commits B1 at 10:30am, B2 at 11:30am. Before either pushes, Alice's log shows: XвҶ’A1вҶ’A2. Bob's log shows: XвҶ’B1вҶ’B2. There is NO single timeline вҖ” there are two independent chains. Wall-clock time is irrelevant to the commit graph; what matters is the parent pointer. A1's parent is X, not B1 (even though B1 happened between A1 and A2 in real time). The histories only merge when one of them explicitly pulls from the other."

-- oracle check:
--   вҠЁ corrected-understanding directly addresses the timeline misconception вҶ’ вң“

