  вҲҙ ...Show that git merge finds the COMMON ANCESTOR commit... contrast with
    rebase: rebase REPLAYS your commits one-by-one...

-- LLM evaluation:

  yield corrected-understanding вүЎ "Git does NOT use timestamps to combine work. It uses the commit graph вҖ” specifically, parent pointers. Merge strategy: git finds the common ancestor (the last commit both developers share), then performs a three-way diff (ancestor vs your changes vs their changes). Conflicts arise when both modified the same lines, regardless of when. The result is a merge commit with two parents. Rebase strategy: instead of creating a merge commit, rebase takes your commits and replays them one-by-one on top of the other developer's latest commit, creating new commits with new parent pointers. The code changes are the same, but the history shape differs: merge preserves the fork-and-join topology, rebase creates a linear sequence. Neither cares about timestamps."

-- oracle check:
--   вҠЁ corrected-understanding directly addresses the timestamp misconception вҶ’ вң“

