  yield question вүЎ "Here's a tricky scenario: You clone a repo at 9am and make two commits at 10:00 AM and 11:00 AM. Your colleague clones the same repo, but she deliberately sets her computer's clock back to yesterday and makes two commits timestamped 3:00 PM and 4:00 PM YESTERDAY. Now you both want to combine your work. Question 1: Does git get confused by the timestamps? Does it try to put her 'yesterday' commits before your 'today' commits? Question 2: Git actually offers you TWO ways to combine the work. Way A creates a new 'combination commit' that ties both histories together. Way B takes your commits and re-does them as if you'd started from her latest commit. Can you guess what the history would look like in each case вҖ” and which one would you prefer for a team project?"
  yield target-understanding вүЎ "Two concepts: (1) Git ignores timestamps for history reconciliation вҖ” it uses parent pointers (graph structure) to find the common ancestor. (2) The fundamental distinction between merge (preserves fork-and-join topology, creates merge commit) and rebase (rewrites your commits to create linear history). The student should begin to articulate a preference and reasoning."

