  yield answer вүЎ "OK so for question 1 вҖ” I'm guessing git does NOT get confused by the timestamps? Because you said earlier that git tracks which commit came from which, like parent pointers. So even if her timestamps say yesterday, git knows her commits came AFTER the original clone point, same as mine. The timestamps are just metadata, not how git organizes things.

For question 2 вҖ” Way A sounds like it creates a snapshot of 'here's what the code looks like when we put both sets of changes together,' and it keeps both branches of history visible. Way B sounds like it pretends I started my work after she finished hers, so the history looks like one straight line.

I think for a team project I'd prefer Way A? Because Way B kind of lies about when I did my work. If something breaks, it would be harder to figure out what happened if the history was rewritten. But Way A might make the log messy with all those combination commits... I can see why teams might disagree about this."
  yield confidence вүЎ "unsure"

