-- LLM evaluation:

  yield remedial-summary вүЎ "MISCONCEPTION LOG вҖ” Teaching session on 'Git rebase vs merge'

Misconception 1 (iteration 0): SHARED TIMELINE FALLACY
Student believed all commits exist on one universal timeline ordered by wall-clock time. CORRECTION: Each git clone has its own independent commit history. Two developers working in parallel have two separate commit chains that diverge from their common starting point. Wall-clock time is irrelevant вҖ” what matters is the parent pointer in each commit.

Misconception 2 (iteration 0): PULL = DOWNLOAD + STACK
Student believed 'git pull' simply downloads remote commits and places them linearly atop local ones. CORRECTION: pull = fetch + merge. Fetch downloads; merge reconciles divergent histories either by creating a merge commit (two parents) or by rebasing (replaying commits to create linear history). Neither is 'stacking.'

Misconception 3 (iteration 1): TIMESTAMP-BASED RECONCILIATION
Student believed git uses commit timestamps to determine ordering when combining work. CORRECTION: Git uses the commit graph (parent pointers) to find the common ancestor and reconcile changes. Timestamps are metadata only вҖ” a backdated commit is handled identically to a correctly-dated one. Merge uses three-way diff from the common ancestor; rebase replays commits based on graph position, not time.

RESOLUTION: After 3 iterations, student demonstrated solid understanding of both merge (preserves fork-and-join topology) and rebase (creates linear history by replaying commits), including the trade-off between auditability and clean history."

-- oracle checks:
